To visualize this two-fold decomposition of the problem structure using TikZ in LaTeX, we can create a diagram that clearly represents the relationships between daily routing/scheduling problems, multi-day solutions, and the final comprehensive plan. Below is the TikZ code to generate this diagram:

```latex
\documentclass[border=10pt]{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzstyle{process} = [rectangle, rounded corners, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=2cm,text centered, draw=black, fill=orange!30]
\tikzstyle{decision} = [diamond, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=2cm, text centered, draw=black, fill=green!30]
\tikzstyle{arrow} = [thick,->,>=stealth]

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

\node (init) [startstop] {Start};
\node (daily_scheduling) [process, below of=init] {Daily Routing/Scheduling Problems};
\node (multi_day_combination) [process, below of=daily_scheduling, yshift=-1cm] {Multi-Day Solutions Combination};
\node (final_plan) [process, below of=multi_day_combination] {Final Comprehensive Plan};

% Draw edges
\draw [arrow] (init) -- (daily_scheduling);
\draw [arrow] (daily_scheduling) -- (multi_day_combination);
\draw [arrow] (multi_day_combination) -- (final_plan);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**:
  - `init`: Represents the start of the process.
  - `daily_scheduling`: Represents the individual daily routing and scheduling problems for each caregiver.
  - `multi_day_combination`: Represents the process of combining daily solutions into multi-day solutions while ensuring the required number of treatments and the minimum number of days between visits.
  - `final_plan`: Represents the final comprehensive plan combining all multi-day solutions to ensure strict continuity of care and minimize overall cost.

- **Edges**:
  - Arrows connect these nodes sequentially, showing the flow from the initial step to the final comprehensive plan.

